  "text": "The Rust trait obligation resolution system implements a sophisticated chain for fulfilling trait obligations and reporting errors when they cannot be satisfied. The chain flows through several key components:\n\n1. **Obligation Forest (compiler/rustc_data_structures/src/obligation_forest/mod.rs)**: The foundational data structure that tracks outstanding obligations as a forest of trees. Each obligation can generate sub-obligations, forming a dependency graph. The ObligationForest manages the state of obligations (pending, completed, or error) and processes them recursively through process_obligations().\n\n2. **Fulfillment Context (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/fulfill.rs)**: The FulfillmentContext wraps an ObligationForest and manages the trait resolution process. It maintains PendingPredicateObligations which combine a PredicateObligation with stalled type variables. The context provides register_obligation() to add new obligations and select() to process them.\n\n3. **Fulfill Processor (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/fulfill.rs)**: The FulfillProcessor implements the ObligationProcessor trait and is the callback used during obligation forest processing. It bridges the obligation forest with the SelectionContext, processing each obligation through trait selection.\n\n4. **Selection Context (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/mod.rs)**: The core selection engine that attempts to select a trait implementation for an obligation. It uses select() to find a matching implementation and returns SelectionResult which can be Ok(Some(selection)), Ok(None) for ambiguous cases, or Err for unsatisfied obligations.\n\n5. **Candidate Assembly (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/candidate_assembly.rs)**: The assemble_candidates() method collects all possible implementations that could satisfy a trait obligation. It considers:\n   - Explicit impls in scope\n   - Trait aliases\n   - Builtin trait implementations (Sized, Copy, Clone, etc.)\n   - Caller's where-clause bounds (param env candidates)\n   - Auto trait implementations\n\n6. **Candidate Confirmation (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/confirmation.rs)**: The confirm_candidate() method validates a selected candidate by:\n   - Unifying the candidate's trait ref with the obligation's trait ref\n   - Collecting nested obligations from the impl\n   - Returning nested PredicateObligations that must also be satisfied\n   - Handling different candidate types (ImplCandidate, ParamCandidate, BuiltinCandidate, etc.)\n\n7. **Error Reporting (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/error_reporting/traits/mod.rs)**: When obligations cannot be fulfilled, the report_fulfillment_errors() method generates user-facing diagnostics. It:\n   - Aggregates errors from failed obligations\n   - Suggests potential fixes (add trait bounds, use type parameters, etc.)\n   - Provides context about which impls were considered but rejected\n   - Reports impl mismatch errors with detailed suggestions\n\nThe complete obligation chain works as follows:\nFulfillmentContext::register_obligation() → FulfillmentContext::select() → ObligationForest::process_obligations() → FulfillProcessor::process_obligation() → SelectionContext::select() → assemble_candidates() → candidate filtering → confirm_candidate() → nested obligations → Error or Success → report_fulfillment_errors()\n\nWhen an obligation fails at any point (no matching impls, nested obligations fail, or type mismatch), the error flows back through the obligation tree, ultimately being reported via the error reporting system which provides helpful diagnostics to the user."
}

